          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">ICC warrant and condemnation</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-27-2.png" alt="ICC warrant and condemnation" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><strong>Summary: An ICC prosecutor has applied for arrest warrants against the supreme leader and chief justice of the Taliban for gender-based persecution.</strong></p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">An International Criminal Court (ICC) Prosecutor applied for arrest warrants against Taliban Supreme Leader Haibatullah Akhundzada and Chief Justice Abdul Hakim Haqqani for crimes against humanity, specifically gender-based persecution. The charges are based on systematic oppression of women and girls, including denial of education, employment, and existence in public life, alongside severe human rights violations like torture and enforced disappearances since August 2021 (<a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-01-2025-h1-4-icc-official-statement" target="_blank">ICC official statement</a>).</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Expert testimony, forensic reports, and Taliban-issued decrees are the evidence being used to support the claims. If the application is approved, this case will be the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-01-2025-h2-5-first-icc-action" target="_blank">first ICC action</a> addressing crimes in Afghanistan, aiming to uphold justice and end impunity for human rights violations under the Taliban regime. A three-judge panel at the ICC will be expected to rule on the prosecution request, which has no set deadline.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The Taliban‚Äôs Ministry of Foreign Affairs <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-01-2025-h2-6-refuted-the-warrants" target="_blank">refuted the warrants</a> as ‚Äúdevoid of just legal basis, duplicitous in nature and politically motivated.‚Äù However, human rights groups, the UN Rapporteur, and Afghan women have <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-01-2025-h2-7-welcomed-the-icc-move" target="_blank">welcomed the ICC‚Äôs move</a>, viewing it as a crucial step toward holding the Taliban accountable for their human rights abuses.</p>
        </mj-text>
