          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">General strike in Serbia</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><strong>Summary: Serbian protests expanded to many sectors of Serbian society that wanted to see accountability from leadership and authorities.</strong></p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
          Protests in Serbia have turned into a nationwide movement, with thousands joining students in a <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-01-2025-h3-8-general-strike" target="_blank">general strike</a> against government corruption. The strikes follow the tragic Novi Sad railway station disaster, which killed 15 people in November. The protests are now being joined by teachers, workers, and professionals, who observed 15 minutes of silence to honor the victims before marching in major cities around Serbia.
</p>
<p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
          Protesters demand accountability from authorities and officials while accusing them of negligence in the canopy collapse linked to a Chinese-led railway renovation. This raises further questions about <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-01-2025-h3-9-chinese-bri-project" target="_blank">Chinese BRI projects</a> in the country. Students have been blockading universities for months, and businesses, cultural institutions, and workers across sectors have joined the strike. Over the weekend, a car drove into the strike, injuring one woman (<a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-01-2025-car-drove-into-the-strike" target="_blank">see video-sensitive content</a>).
</p>
<p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
          Aleksandar Vucic‚Äôs government dismissed the protests despite the widespread calls for change. He held a counter rally in Jagodina and accused foreign forces of meddling in Serbia‚Äôs affairs. Serbia is an EU candidate state with grievances against the West, particularly over the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-27-01-2025-h3-10-1999-nato-bombing" target="_blank">1999 NATO bombing</a>. While Serbia is friendly to China, it has grown skeptical of Chinese projects' safety and feels some projects are ‚Äúdebt traps.‚Äù
</p>
        </mj-text>
